"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104977","Department for Education","false","2019-04-02","<p>​Outdoor air quality is a responsibility of local authorities. Where there are concerns about air quality, a local authority must prepare an air quality action plan. The Department has recently published guidance (Building Bulletin 101) on achieving good indoor air quality in new and refurbished schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-04-02T16:41:50.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104977/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104977/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-25","Schools: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to improve air quality outside schools.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","236566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104978","Home Office","false","2019-04-02","<p>The Home Office have worked closely with the All-Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) for International Freedom of Religion or Belief and the Asylum Advocacy Group (AAG) for many years, to help improve their approach to religious based claims and have recently worked with them to develop and produce a specialist training package.</p><p>The aim of this course is to ensure that where religion or belief is raised in an asylum claim, asylum decision makers appropriately consider all the available evidence in accordance International, European &amp; Domestic law and Home Office Asylum Policy, when interviewing asylum applicants and making decisions on their claims.</p><p>The course will be rolled out to Asylum Senior Caseworkers and Technical Specialists in April 2019 and all asylum Decision Makers over the course of the subsequent three months.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-04-02T15:54:43.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104978/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104978/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-25","Asylum: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress his Department has made on the (a) production and (b) rollout of compulsory training on religion or belief claims for all asylum assessors, announced in October 2018.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","236243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104979","Department for Education","false","2019-04-02","<p>​The Children’s Social Care myth busting guide was intended to bring clarity to some parts of guidance that had been raised with the department. However, the points raised by Article 39 suggest that the guide did not achieve that. Rather than divert time and resources to litigation we decided to withdraw the guide in its present form pending a full reconsideration of its contents.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-04-02T14:47:05.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104979/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104979/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-25","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons he has withdrawn his Department's myth-busting guide for local authorities on their obligations on children's care; and what plans he has to issue a revised guide.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","236482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104980","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>​There are no plans to change existing reciprocal healthcare arrangements between the United Kingdom and The Republic of Malta following the United Kingdom's departure from the European Union. The UK Government wants to continue our existing arrangements with Malta, so that no-one faces sudden changes to how they obtain healthcare. Discussions about how to achieve this aim are continuing.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-04-01T13:51:30.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104980/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104980/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Malta: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the bilateral agreements between the UK and Malta, including the agreement that Maltese citizens can receive free healthcare treatment in the UK, will be maintained after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","236483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104981","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-29","<p>In line with NHS England’s usual processes, an Equalities Impact Assessment will be undertaken where it is certain that there could be substantive changes to service provision. In relation to the outcome of the Lot 4 procurement, this would be triggered in the event there was no alternative proposal but to move the service from the Churchill Hospital site to another location in Oxford.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has not yet conducted the Equalities Impact Assessment because all parties, including Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, are committed to ensuring that PET-CT services are retained on the Churchill site, as part of a wider network of provision and partnership arrangement between both the Trust and InHealth. NHS England is due to present a report to Oxfordshire’s joint Health Overview and Scrutiny Committee on 4 April 2019, setting out the proposals and next steps.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-03-29T14:45:05.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104981/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104981/answer","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104981/answer/previousversion/110763","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-25","Tomography: Oxford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will place in the Library any impact assessment conducted on the proposed privatisation of the PET-CT scan service in Oxford.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","236567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104982","Home Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>In December 2018, the Government set out its proposals in “the UK’s future Skills-based Immigration System” White Paper. The White Paper proposals include a new route for skilled workers which will be open to anyone at RQF level 3 and above, irrespective of where they are applying from. This route will not be capped allowing all of those who meet our requirements to come to the UK.</p><p>The White Paper also includes a transitional route for temporary workers which will be open to anyone from qualifying countries, wishing to fill positions at any skill level, for up to 12 months. We do not intend to impose a cap on the number of people wishing to use the route.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","236570","2019-03-28T17:21:01.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104982/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104982/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-25","Migrant Workers: NHS and Social Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps he is taking to ensure that (a) NHS workers and (b) care workers can be recruited from (i) EU and (ii) non-EU countries after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","236568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104983","Home Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>We have been clear that we want all EU nationals, including those working in the NHS and the care sector, to stay in the UK after we leave the EU.</p><p>In their report, EEA migration in the UK, the independent Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) recommended maintaining the existing system of salary thresholds.</p><p>The Government has been clear that we will undertake an extensive programme of engagement with a wide range of stakeholders across the UK, including with the private, public and voluntary sector and local government, as well as industry representatives and individual businesses before taking a final decision on the level of salary thresholds.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-03-28T17:13:46.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104983/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104983/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-25","Migrant Workers: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the salary exemption for nurses on Tier 2 visas will remain his policy after the UK leaves the EU; and what plans he has to extend that exemption to EEA citizens.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","236569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104984","Home Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>In December 2018, the Government set out its proposals in “the UK’s future Skills-based Immigration System” White Paper. The White Paper proposals include a new route for skilled workers which will be open to anyone at RQF level 3 and above, irrespective of where they are applying from. This route will not be capped allowing all of those who meet our requirements to come to the UK.</p><p>The White Paper also includes a transitional route for temporary workers which will be open to anyone from qualifying countries, wishing to fill positions at any skill level, for up to 12 months. We do not intend to impose a cap on the number of people wishing to use the route.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","236568","2019-03-28T17:21:01.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104984/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104984/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-25","Migrant Workers: Social Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps he is taking to ensure that care workers from EU Member States can work in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","236570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104985","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-28","<p>The Department has made no such an assessment.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-03-28T16:14:56.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104985/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104985/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-25","Asthma: Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of adding asthma to the list of medical exemptions for prescription charges.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","236484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104986","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-28","<p>Households can have their benefits capped either under Housing Benefit, or under Universal Credit. The latest statistics were published in February 2019, covering households capped to November 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Under Housing Benefit, statistics on the number of households capped in the geographical areas requested by banded, weekly cap amount, is published and available at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a> (‘Benefit Cap’, ‘Point in Time caseload’ table). Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Under Universal Credit, statistics on the number of households capped by banded, weekly cap amount can be found in the February 2019 official statistics release (Table 9, <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-cap-number-of-households-capped-to-november-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-cap-number-of-households-capped-to-november-2018</a>).</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-03-28T17:30:36.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104986/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104986/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-25","Housing Benefit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 22 March 2019 to Question 234158 on Public Sector: Pensions, what estimate she has made of the average amount of benefit payment not received per household in each local authority area in Wales as a result of the imposition of the benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","236340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104987","Department for International Development","false","2019-03-28","<p>The 175 roles referenced in the previous answer of 20 March 2019 formed the basis of a ‘tranche’ of potential matches for DFID to consider. DFID has provisionally matched to over half of these and are focussing on progressing these matches into actual deployments as appropriate. The work to match and deploy to cross-government priorities is iterative and likely to continue in the immediate future, as DFID continues to support other government departments with increased demands.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-03-28T17:05:10.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104987/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104987/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-25","Department for International Development: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 20 March 2019 to Question 234783 on Department for International Development: Secondment, when she will decide whether the 175 staff in her Department are placed with other Departments.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","236571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104988","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>A full list of those 52 multilateral treaties from which the UK has unilaterally withdrawn since 1 January 1988 is attached.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-03-28T16:55:15.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104988/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104988/answer","PQ TREATIES THE UK HAS WITHDRAWN FROM SINCE 1 JANUARY 1988.docx","Treaties the UK has withdrawn from since 01.01.88","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104988/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 March 2019 to Question 234199 on Treaties, if he will provide a full list naming each of the 52 multilateral treaties from which the UK has unilaterally withdrawn since 1 January 1988.","false","Biography information for Neil O'Brien","Harborough","Neil O'Brien","236572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104989","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-28","<p>The Government understands the importance of accessible on-board information in helping bus passengers to travel with confidence, and in Summer 2018 published a public consultation on proposals to require its provision on local bus services throughout Great Britain. This follows the Government’s commitment, set out in the Inclusive Transport Strategy, to invest £2 million towards ensuring that audio visual equipment is installed on buses.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to analyse responses to the consultation and expect to announce our next steps regarding the making of Regulations and publication of guidance later in the year.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-03-28T14:25:14.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104989/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104989/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-25","Bus Services: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to implement audio visual announcements on buses.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","236573"
